t3627.text: We should absolutely be outraged and frustrated and saddened by these deaths - by any significant act of violence in the community - but there are aspects of this take on the issue that deserve a little more explanation.

t3628.text: It doesn’t necessarily make it right or fair that these deaths don’t land on the front page every single time, but I do think it deserves some context and explanation. Court reporters also often do an incredible job bringing these stories to the public down the track.

t3629.text: I honestly can’t remember the last time a murder did not get media coverage, at least in Victoria.

t3630.text: Also, when a matter is before the court, it means police and other authorities don’t have as much freedom to comment or contribute to the story because sub judice applies. This means they cannot contribute to the narrative (though of course others can).

t3631.text: Offences where there is family violence involved often have a greater complexity for media, especially if suppression orders exist that are designed to protect remaining family members.

t3632.text: To divert from footy for a second, I just want to expand on this slightly. In my experience, murders where the offender is arrested at the scene tend to get the least amount of media coverage. Where the parties are known to each other, often even less.https://twitter.com/Mamamia/status/1225658200034168837 …
